  "text": " that, you know, didn't invest in Brex, but I actually know quite well, that says that Brex is the last good fintech idea. And I'm like, I don't think that's true. I think it's the last sexy good one. But I think there's a lot there. But I think one thing that changed my mind a lot about company building, I think if I were to write a book about how to build a company, there would be two parts. Part one takes six months. Part two takes 10 years. and they're 50% importance of each. And the part one is just finding what you're going to do and who you're going to do it with. And I think the initial conditions are like highly underestimated. There's this belief that I can just pivot my way around into an idea that works. And sure, that's true to some degree. But once you start something that has a little bit of traction, it's really hard to pivot away into something else. and I think people just don't anticipate how much of just finding a good idea is still really damn important and Brax was a really good idea I mean a lot of the credit is just the idea yes I think we executed well in some ways but I think the idea was just that good and if I were to start something again I would certainly spend a lot of time getting that part right and if that isn't a good place then the other 50% is the 10 year journey of leveraging those tailwinds so to speak. Pedro, final one. What question do you never ask that you really think you should be asked? The battle inside you, not the one outside you. Like, how do you, how do you how do you stay motivated and energized and excited when things get harder And I don see people talking enough about that because Do you feel you can show that level of vulnerability when you have a thousand people? I do. I mean, I talk about this shit a lot with my team. And I wrote about it. I mean, we did this mental health series called Catharsis, where we have like founders talking about their own mental health journeys, which is really hard to convince people to do, by the way. Most people don't like talking about it openly, but I just talk to founders day in and day out and customers day in and day out, and that's the same thing everyone's going through. You need to find ways of how do you frame your mind and how do you frame the work you're doing around something that gives you purpose and gives you joy? Because if you are focused on the outcome, if you're just focused on and you don't enjoy the process, the math doesn't add up. It just does not make any sense. And I think a lot of the point about not being apologetic and how you run the company, Honestly, 50% of the value is just doing it in a way that you get energy from the process. Because if you don't get energy from the process and the process is not rewarding on its own and you're just focused on the outcome, it's going to suck. It's going to take a lot of time and a lot of energy and more energy than you think because you need the energy that comes from the actual process being enjoyable. Pedro, I've loved doing this. I know I send you schedules and your team goes through them diligently and I just don't speak to them. But thank you so much for being so open. And I've really so enjoyed having you on. Likewise. I really appreciate it, Harry. Great being here and really appreciate the time. You're a great interviewer.",
